Just to clarify, on projects like this, I usually have two levels of tests:
user tests that verify that the end user sees what she expects (running in
the container, even through the browser), and developer tests that verify
that my classes work as I expect.  For user tests, it&#39;s essential to have
all the components in place.  For developer tests, it&#39;s counter-productive:
I want to understand what my code does independently of what services are
provided by third-party containers or servers, and I also want to run
developer tests often and fast.

I think this is the same thing Vishal is saying below, but I wanted a chance
to rephrase it a little.  Thanks,

   David Saff

On 11/2/06, Vishal Vishnoi &lt;vvishnoi@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Use Cactus
&gt; (http://jakarta.apache.org/cactus/writing/howto_testcase.html).  It&#39;s
&gt; very easy to package you test and run them on server side. They also
&gt; have documentation on how to test EJB  or any regular JUnit test in the
&gt; container.
&gt;
&gt; For higher level testing (i.e testing like a customer),  if you need to
&gt; verify something in container, then verify it in container. Don&#39;t try to
&gt; run it outside, otherwise the whole purpose of testing is lost.
&gt;
&gt; --Vishal
